00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:07.190
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson: Before
introducing the speakers,

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:11.440
I want to say as we know,
Alan was the founding director

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:14.360
of the American Folklife
Center and in that role,

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:17.450
he was a direct successor
to Benjamin Botkin,

00:02:17.450 --> 00:02:21.290
head of the library's
folklore section in the 1940's.

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:25.110
So, it's appropriate that we're
presenting this evening event

00:02:25.110 --> 00:02:30.900
of talks and music about
Alan as part of this series.

00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:35.330
This series also allows us to
present the, and highlight,

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:38.670
the work of the best
in leading scholars,

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:42.550
experts in the disciplines of
folklore at the musicology,

00:02:42.550 --> 00:02:45.160
oral history, and
cultural heritage.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:47.810
It also allows us to
enhance the collections

00:02:47.810 --> 00:02:50.850
of the American Folklife
Center, and for the center

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:54.970
and the library, the Botkin
lectures form an important facet

00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:57.310
of our acquisitions activities.

00:02:57.310 --> 00:03:00.630
Each lecture is videotaped
as you can gather,

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:03.880
with these bright lights,
and it becomes part

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:06.890
of the permanent
collections of the center.

00:03:06.890 --> 00:03:11.440
So, the lectures are going to
be posted later as a webcast

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:14.400
on the libraries website
where they will be available

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:17.750
to people throughout the world
and for generations to come.

00:03:17.750 --> 00:03:22.670
