on right now or anything

00:03:22.670 --> 00:03:28.980
that might ring later, please
turn it off at this time.

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:33.220
So, Alan, being the director of
the American Folklife Center,

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:40.060
from 1976, I think September
of 1976 through June of 1999,

00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:41.940
that was only one of many roles

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:46.060
that Alan assumed throughout
his lifetime in his efforts

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:52.290
to preserve and carry forward
folk cultural traditions.

00:03:52.290 --> 00:03:55.680
Alan was a musician, an
artist, a native Floridian,

00:03:55.680 --> 00:04:00.610
a southern gentleman, a writer,
an administrator with a vision,

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:02.360
folklorist, researcher,

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:05.170
president of the
American Folklore Society,

00:04:05.170 --> 00:04:08.130
a member of numerous
boards and so much more.

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:12.290
Our speakers this evening
will be addressing many

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:16.560
of these different facets and
aspects of Alan's contributions,

00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:18.780
but before I introduce
them I did want

00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:22.070
to mention one dimension
of Alan's work

00:04:22.070 --> 00:04:25.150
that I think has received very
little attention over the years

00:04:25.150 --> 00:04:30.240
and that is Alan's work to raise
the profile of philanthropy

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.810
and giving for the folk
and traditional arts.

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:37.870
Alan came to D.C and the
federal government in the 1970's

00:04:37.870 --> 00:04:40.480
and we know that
was a very heaty

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:43.720
and sometimes turbulent
time for cultural heritage

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:48.540
and preservation legislation
and government support and Alan

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:51.760
and several other folklore
luminaries at that time,

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:55.350
Archie Green, Bess Lomax
Hawes, and Ralph Rinzler,

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:58.350
among them were right
there at the very beginning

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:00.910
and they helped build
this foundation

00:05:00.910 --> 00:05:04.370
for several public
folklore institutions

00:05:04.370 --> 00:05:07.930
and perhaps Alan's work at the
national endowment for the arts

00:05:07.930 --> 00:05:11.960
as an initial head of the folk
arts program provided him a

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:15.760
window for him to understand
the importance of support.

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:19.900
And not only to provide
needed financial resources,

00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:24.060
but also to lend legitimacy
and validation to the diversity

00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:28.250
of folk and traditional culture
in the United States and beyond.

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:32.460
But, with so much emphasis on
public support, Alan and others,

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:34.600
Joe Wilson, Archie Green,

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:38.700
also recognized the critical
importance of galvanizing

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:42.100
and strengthening private
and individual support

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:44.260
for the grass roots
vernacular culture

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:46.570
that we all hold so dear.

00:05:46.570 --> 00:05:49.820
Alan and others helped to
find the fund for folk culture

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:53.730
in 1991 and held the
planning meetings right here

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:55.030
in the library.

00:05:55.030 --> 00:05:58.120
Alan was the first chair of
the board of trustees and in

00:05:58.120 --> 00:06:01.390
that capacity, helped guide
the direction of that fund

00:06:01.390 --> 00:06:05.160
to help serve as an advocate and
liaison for the field of folk

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:09.370
and traditional arts with
private philanthropy.

00:06:09.370 --> 00:06:14.720
In that role, over about a
15-year span, they steered over,

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:19.100
well over $10 million
dollars of new support

00:06:19.100 --> 00:06:23.450
to the folk arts field which is
pretty amazing and in his work

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:24.750
at the folklife center,

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:28.930
Alan also established several
endowments and gift funds

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:32.130
to support the work of
the center and others

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:34.980
and individuals to
do their work.

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:39.640
The Ray Virginia Alan fund, the
Blant Nolan fund, the Gerald

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:42.470
and Karen Parson's
fund and of course,

00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:46.240
the Henry Reed fund
for folk artists.

00:06:46.240 --> 00:06:48.350
On the occasion of
Alan's retirement,

00:06:48.350 --> 00:06:51.800
Alan and Karen Jabbour, with
several other individuals,

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:55.590
established the fund, the
Henry Reed fund in 2000.

00:06:55.590 --> 00:07:00.730
It honors Alan's musical mentor,
West Virginia fiddler Henry Reed

00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:03.610
and provides support
for folk artists

00:07:03.610 --> 00:07:08.840
or to projects benefiting folk
artists whether it be a program,

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:15.320
a recording project, a,
providing opportunities

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:19.450
for artists to do research and
to work with other artists.

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:23.360
Since 2004, the Henry Reed
fund has provided awards

00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:28.160
to 10 individuals and I know we
have several individuals here

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:31.590
tonight, perhaps some
Henry Reed recipients,

00:07:31.590 --> 00:07:35.230
but I know we also have many
individuals who have given

00:07:35.230 --> 00:07:37.590
to the Henry Reed
fund and I truly want

00:07:37.590 --> 00:07:41.210
to thank you for doing that.

00:07:41.210 --> 00:07:44.960
I also want to acknowledge
Henry Reed's son,

00:07:44.960 --> 00:07:47.550
Dean Reed who is
here with us tonight

00:07:47.550 --> 00:07:49.710
and Henry Reed's
grandson, Terry,

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:51.510
if you would stand
