00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:02.530
&gt;&gt; CARL FLEISHHAUER:
Thank you Betsy

00:11:02.530 --> 00:11:05.860
and I'm pleased to be here.

00:11:05.860 --> 00:11:09.040
What I'm going to talk
about, as Betsy suggested,

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:12.510
is Alan as the leader of
the center from the start.

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:15.450
A little about his thinking,
activities at the center

00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:19.690
and policy development in
federal, cultural sector.

00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:22.970
The study and performance
of music that Alan did

00:11:22.970 --> 00:11:27.720
so well will be the subject
of the next presentations.

00:11:27.720 --> 00:11:31.040
Let me start with Alan
and strategic planning.

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:33.510
This is a bureaucratic
exorcise that tends

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:36.020
to repeat at regular intervals.

00:11:36.020 --> 00:11:40.190
I should know after 40 years
here at the library proceeded

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:44.810
by working a university and on
the boards of some non-profits.

00:11:44.810 --> 00:11:47.860
All too often, staff or
board members are put

00:11:47.860 --> 00:11:50.040
through agonizing
committee discussions

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:52.570
that eagled impenetrable
documents written

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:55.060
in bureaucratese.

00:11:55.060 --> 00:11:56.980
Not so with Alan.

00:11:56.980 --> 00:12:00.430
Even as the center first took
shape, planning moved forward

00:12:00.430 --> 00:12:03.240
in semiformal 2-way
conversations

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:06.510
with the center staff and
the folklife center board.

00:12:06.510 --> 00:12:08.370
Alan listened as much

00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:11.630
as he imparted insights
and information.

00:12:11.630 --> 00:12:14.060
He was an inveterate
telephone caller,

00:12:14.060 --> 00:12:17.660
especially before
email was prevalent.

00:12:17.660 --> 00:12:21.410
As ideas took shape, Alan
had 2 advantages over most

00:12:21.410 --> 00:12:24.950
of his conversation
partners, solid experience

00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:27.880
at the library gained when
he was head of the archive

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:33.290
of folksong from 1969
to 1974 and a sense

00:12:33.290 --> 00:12:36.670
of the federal context for
cultural activities resulting

00:12:36.670 --> 00:12:39.320
from his work at the
library and as the head

00:12:39.320 --> 00:12:42.080
of the new folk arts program
at the national endowment

00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:46.200
for the arts from 74 to 76.

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:50.740
That work was under the
estimable chairman Nancy Hanks

00:12:50.740 --> 00:12:54.100
and I remember a
conversation from that period.

00:12:54.100 --> 00:12:56.890
Here's how it works
Carl, Alan said,

00:12:56.890 --> 00:13:00.050
if the letter awards a
grant, Nancy signs it.

00:13:00.050 --> 00:13:06.150
If it says no, we're
sorry, then I sign it.

00:13:06.150 --> 00:13:09.990
Translating plans into action
sometimes required staff members

00:13:09.990 --> 00:13:11.880
to read before the lines.

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:14.790
For important matters,
of course, Alan conferred

00:13:14.790 --> 00:13:18.130
with the center's board and with
the library chain of command,

00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:22.560
often but not always, aligned
with one another, but for staff

00:13:22.560 --> 00:13:25.350
like me, some actions
just seemed to happen.

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:27.650
You could be surprised.

00:13:27.650 --> 00:13:29.980
Of course, usually,
they had been heralded

00:13:29.980 --> 00:13:32.390
by earlier discussion
and marched in step

00:13:32.390 --> 00:13:33.860
with the center's mission.

00:13:33.860 --> 00:13:36.660
Archie Green's excellent
wording embedded

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:39.840
in the center's enabling
legislation,

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:41.140
but here's an example.

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:43.960
Alan's academic background
was rooted in music

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:45.860
and ballad scholarship
and he wanted

00:13:45.860 --> 00:13:48.160
to be sure the center's
program was as broad

00:13:48.160 --> 00:13:50.740
as the term folk life.

00:13:50.740 --> 00:13:53.790
Actions to advance this
goal popped into view

00:13:53.790 --> 00:13:56.440
in Alan's earlier hiring.

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:58.340
Adding Rusty Marshall
to the staff.

00:13:58.340 --> 00:14:00.980
Rusty had been a student of
Henry Glassy and was immersed

00:14:00.980 --> 00:14:04.490
in folk architecture
and material culture

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:07.300
and Elena [inaudible],
a Lithuanian American

00:14:07.300 --> 00:14:10.840
with great insights into the
evolving expressive culture

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:13.710
of those who came from Europe.

00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:17.370
There was also carry over from a
project that Alan helped launch

00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:18.930
when he was at the archive.

00:14:18.930 --> 00:14:22.990
[inaudible] Spots was folk
music of America record albums.

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:24.340
Work that flowed into one

00:14:24.340 --> 00:14:29.060
of the new center's first public
events, symposium and book,

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:32.270
ethnic recording in America.

00:14:32.270 --> 00:14:35.420
Speaking of ethnicity,
Alan rarely talked

00:14:35.420 --> 00:14:40.660
about his own family history,
but in 2007, a writer picked

00:14:40.660 --> 00:14:42.920
up his remarks about
his field work

00:14:42.920 --> 00:14:45.100
with the Virginia
fiddler Henry Reed.

00:14:45.100 --> 00:14:46.670
Reed's father had immigrated

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:50.870
from Ireland while Alan's
had come from Syria.

00:14:50.870 --> 00:14:54.420
Quote, your family story telling
creates a felt connection

00:14:54.420 --> 00:14:56.300
between your past
and your present life

00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:58.480
in America, Alan said.

00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:01.870
It's curious that my father
was the immigrant and I ended

00:15:01.870 --> 00:15:04.020
up being the most
attentive person

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:07.720
to certain cultural
traditions here.

00:15:07.720 --> 00:15:10.540
Regarding communication,
Alan's descriptions

00:15:10.540 --> 00:15:13.140
of the center's accomplishments
showed a real knack

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:15.410
for putting a range of
events and activities

00:15:15.410 --> 00:15:17.870
into a coherent statement.

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:20.880
The quarterly newsletter was
an excellent vehicle for this

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:25.270
and other topics and for about
10 years, Alan made good use

00:15:25.270 --> 00:15:26.910
of the director's column.

00:15:26.910 --> 00:15:31.660
He once said, the newsletter
gives you news and views

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:34.700
and people tell me the views
are the most interesting.

00:15:34.700 --> 00:15:37.600
On 3 occasions, Alan
drafted reviews

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:39.920
of the center's accomplishments.

00:15:39.920 --> 00:15:44.430
Short ones at the 5 and
10-year marks in 1981 and 1986

00:15:44.430 --> 00:15:50.380
and 17,000 word offering
for the 20th in 1996.

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:53.690
Free of bureaucratic jargon,
these reports paint a picture

00:15:53.690 --> 00:15:58.690
of a successive, successful
program, upbeat and affirming

00:15:58.690 --> 00:16:02.540
to be sure and here we
tip the hat to Jim Hardon

00:16:02.540 --> 00:16:06.480
who edited the newsletter
through this period.

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:08.900
The center's agenda
reflected a range

00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:10.880
of advice from multiple voices.

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:14.030
Nevertheless, Alan was the
nerve center for the ideas

00:16:14.030 --> 00:16:16.380
that were translated
into action.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:18.580
Some were topical
like ethnic groups

00:16:18.580 --> 00:16:22.410
and material culture while
others concerned activities.

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:27.460
For example, exhibitions,
publications and concerts.

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:30.380
The first concert was
staged within weeks

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:32.300
of the center's establishment.

00:16:32.300 --> 00:16:34.800
When Alan wrote about
it 20 years later,

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:38.110
he signaled the value of
the series not only in terms

00:16:38.110 --> 00:16:41.550
of artistic expression and the
celebration of community arts,

00:16:41.550 --> 00:16:44.240
but also in terms of
support for institutional

00:16:44.240 --> 00:16:46.430
and congressional relations.

00:16:46.430 --> 00:16:50.590
The audience, Alan said, was
quote, dominated by library

00:16:50.590 --> 00:16:53.600
and capitol hill staffers,
making it for years,

00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:55.840
the center's public
face on the hill.

00:16:55.840 --> 00:17:00.770
Alan guided the center to other
forms of public communication

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:04.880
such as a CD publishing
venture with Rounder Records

00:17:04.880 --> 00:17:08.720
and during Alan's first decade
as director, the center began

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:10.910
to provide access
via the internet.

00:17:10.910 --> 00:17:14.820
Finding aids before the
immergence of the world wide web

00:17:14.820 --> 00:17:16.350
and after 1994,

00:17:16.350 --> 00:17:21.040
online multimedia collections
accessed via the web.

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:24.920
Exhibitions illuminated subjects
ranging from ethnic recording

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:28.470
to Nevada Buckaroos here
with the Smithsonian

00:17:28.470 --> 00:17:30.120
to folk life in Rhode Island.

00:17:30.120 --> 00:17:34.100
A photo display in the U.S
senate office building.

00:17:34.100 --> 00:17:37.650
Exhibits provided visibility
not only for the senate,

00:17:37.650 --> 00:17:39.740
but also with the white house.

00:17:39.740 --> 00:17:41.290
First lady Rosalynn Carter

00:17:41.290 --> 00:17:44.490
and daughter Amy opened an
installation on Georgia folk art

00:17:44.490 --> 00:17:46.860
and folk life in 1978,

00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:50.160
while president Mrs. Regan
opened the American Cowboy

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:52.620
Exhibition in 1983.

00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:57.350
During the 1980's, the center
director Alan attended meetings

00:17:57.350 --> 00:17:59.790
of the world intellectual
property organization

00:17:59.790 --> 00:18:03.750
to discuss intellectual
property and folk expression.

00:18:03.750 --> 00:18:06.930
His article for UNESCO's
copyright bulletin noted

00:18:06.930 --> 00:18:10.830
that copyright law focused on
the rights of an individual

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:14.550
or incorporated entity in
contrast to the way that,

00:18:14.550 --> 00:18:18.810
in many tradition communities,
creative expression is seen

00:18:18.810 --> 00:18:20.130
as belonging to groups.

00:18:20.130 --> 00:18:22.140
[ Background noise ]

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:23.540
&gt;&gt; CARL FLEISHHAUER:
Protecting folklore, Alan wrote,

00:18:23.540 --> 00:18:25.810
means acknowledging
an intermediate sphere

00:18:25.810 --> 00:18:28.930
of intellectual property rights
between individual rights

00:18:28.930 --> 00:18:30.940
on the one hand and
the national,

00:18:30.940 --> 00:18:34.070
international public
domain on the other in terms

00:18:34.070 --> 00:18:36.670
of legal history and
legal frameworks,

00:18:36.670 --> 00:18:39.790
this is a radical idea.

00:18:39.790 --> 00:18:43.050
Meanwhile, as we look back,
our attention is often drawn

00:18:43.050 --> 00:18:45.010
to the center's field
work projects.

00:18:45.010 --> 00:18:49.540
Alan staged more than a
dozen from 1977 to 1994,

00:18:49.540 --> 00:18:54.290
rural and urban like this New
Jersey pair in the pinelands

00:18:54.290 --> 00:18:57.500
and in industrial Patterson.

00:18:57.500 --> 00:18:58.910
These were team projects

00:18:58.910 --> 00:19:02.690
with mostly youthful workers
although the 1979 team

00:19:02.690 --> 00:19:05.860
in Rhode Island included
professor Kenny Goldstein,

00:19:05.860 --> 00:19:09.140
wearing the white shirt in
this team meeting in a project

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:13.670
that was led by our recently
departed college Peter Bardis.

00:19:13.670 --> 00:19:16.250
May he rest in peace.

00:19:16.250 --> 00:19:19.820
These were generally survey
projects lasting a month or 2.

00:19:19.820 --> 00:19:22.230
Some cooperatively with
the national park service,

00:19:22.230 --> 00:19:23.930
some with state arts councils.

00:19:23.930 --> 00:19:27.690
Alan often visited
and participated.

00:19:27.690 --> 00:19:30.840
Field projects were integrated
into the center's program

00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:32.230
in addition to exhibits,

00:19:32.230 --> 00:19:35.890
products included David Taylor's
book on Italian Americans

00:19:35.890 --> 00:19:38.390
in the west from a
multistate survey,

00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:41.820
Charles Woolf's double album
of Blueridge religious music,

00:19:41.820 --> 00:19:44.920
and Mary Huffard's
evocative web collections

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:49.050
from West Virginia's
coal fields and more.

00:19:49.050 --> 00:19:51.270
Meanwhile, for Native
American music,

00:19:51.270 --> 00:19:54.890
the federal cylinder
preservation project came first,

00:19:54.890 --> 00:19:57.580
field work came second.

00:19:57.580 --> 00:20:00.450
Cylinder recordings of the
Omaha Tribe were created

00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:05.790
by Alice Fletcher and Francis La
Flesche between 1895 and 1905.

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:11.310
In 1983, Alan visited the
Omaha Indian reservation

00:20:11.310 --> 00:20:15.400
to share copies with the tribal
council and to seek agreement

00:20:15.400 --> 00:20:18.280
on selection and publication.

00:20:18.280 --> 00:20:23.010
When he played some examples,
2 elderly men were present.

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:25.970
When John Turner began
singing, Alan wrote,

00:20:25.970 --> 00:20:28.860
I knew we were home free.

00:20:28.860 --> 00:20:31.010
Soon, the center
published album,

00:20:31.010 --> 00:20:35.610
documented 2 Omaha powwows,
created a website and co-hosted

00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:37.920
by the tribe's cultural
representative,

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:41.500
staged a performance
at the library.

00:20:41.500 --> 00:20:43.500
The field work projects
contributed

00:20:43.500 --> 00:20:46.430
to policy development,
most strikingly in relation

00:20:46.430 --> 00:20:48.390
to historic preservation

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:51.220
where the federal legal
apparatus expanded

00:20:51.220 --> 00:20:55.300
from the 1960's to the
1990's with a fresh interest

00:20:55.300 --> 00:20:59.410
in what was called intangible
elements of cultural heritage.

00:20:59.410 --> 00:21:05.170
In 1977 and 78, national park
service director William Wayland

00:21:05.170 --> 00:21:07.240
was on the center's
board and Alan worked

00:21:07.240 --> 00:21:09.330
with park service
representatives to frame

00:21:09.330 --> 00:21:12.360
up a field project on
the Blueridge parkway

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:16.770
to provide material for
park interpretive programs.

00:21:16.770 --> 00:21:18.440
In later cooperative projects

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:21.860
like the 1983 pinelands
folklife project in New Jersey,

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:25.500
the center provided not only
support for interpretation,

00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:28.900
but also for park service
planning efforts including land

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:32.970
use concepts that were sensitive
to neighboring communities.

00:21:32.970 --> 00:21:36.150
By the 1980's, Alan wrote,

00:21:36.150 --> 00:21:38.540
national park service
planners quote,

00:21:38.540 --> 00:21:41.530
represent a new generation
of professionals

00:21:41.530 --> 00:21:44.830
who have been gradually
abandoning the acquire control

00:21:44.830 --> 00:21:48.380
and manage model for national
parks and exploring models

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:51.730
for cooperation with local
communities operating

00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:56.070
on the premise that local people
should be enlisted, not evicted.

00:21:56.070 --> 00:22:00.680
In 1985, the center joined
Utah's Historic Preservation

00:22:00.680 --> 00:22:03.570
Agency to carry out a field
project in Grouse Creek.

00:22:03.570 --> 00:22:08.780
In the 1987 a park service
project in Iowa Massachusetts.

00:22:08.780 --> 00:22:10.080
Meanwhile, the impact

00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:14.000
of the early field projects
influenced the center's

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:18.140
recommendations concerning
historic preservation policy

00:22:18.140 --> 00:22:22.590
in Ormand Loomis's 1983
report, cultural conservation,

00:22:22.590 --> 00:22:27.050
the protection of cultural
heritage in the United States.

00:22:27.050 --> 00:22:30.030
The field projects added
to the library's holdings

00:22:30.030 --> 00:22:31.820
of archival collections.

00:22:31.820 --> 00:22:33.620
Their organization, description,

00:22:33.620 --> 00:22:37.490
and preservation
received a boost in 1978

00:22:37.490 --> 00:22:40.610
when the folk archive was
brought into the center.

00:22:40.610 --> 00:22:43.450
Founded by Robert
Gordan in 1928,

00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:47.350
the archive had long been part
of the library's music division.

00:22:47.350 --> 00:22:51.230
Alan used his skills as
a diplomat and negotiator

00:22:51.230 --> 00:22:53.170
to find an acceptable
arrangement

00:22:53.170 --> 00:22:56.250
for that administrative move.

00:22:56.250 --> 00:22:59.020
When Alan talked about
the field work projects,

00:22:59.020 --> 00:23:03.090
he emphasized their debt
to New Deal era work,

00:23:03.090 --> 00:23:04.800
the federal writer's project,

00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:07.510
photography from the foreign
security administration

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:09.950
and of course, the work
of John and Alan Lomax

00:23:09.950 --> 00:23:12.350
and their cohorts,
Herbert Halpert,

00:23:12.350 --> 00:23:16.480
Sidney Robertson Cowell, Ben
Botkin, and Charles Seeger,

00:23:16.480 --> 00:23:18.770
a personal favorite of Alan's.

00:23:18.770 --> 00:23:20.630
These predecessors, Alan wrote,

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:24.780
modeled quote, a
documentary cycle.

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:28.530
Field work, collection building
and subsequent public outreach

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:32.530
and as we have seen, Alan pushed
the center quoting him again

00:23:32.530 --> 00:23:36.010
to recycle documents
back into cultural use.

00:23:36.010 --> 00:23:37.430
[ Background noise ]

00:23:37.430 --> 00:23:39.670
&gt;&gt; CARL FLEISHHAUER: Alan
continued to enact this cycle

00:23:39.670 --> 00:23:40.980
in his retirement years

00:23:40.980 --> 00:23:43.090
in the great Smoky
Mountains National Park.

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:47.410
Alan, Ted Coil, and Karen Singer
Jabbour documented cemetery

00:23:47.410 --> 00:23:52.440
traditions, especially the
celebration of Decoration Day.

00:23:52.440 --> 00:23:56.150
The work was initially for an
environmental impact statement.

00:23:56.150 --> 00:23:57.640
A push for the recognition

00:23:57.640 --> 00:24:01.520
of non-Native American
tradition cultural properties

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:06.210
in the environmental
impact process.

00:24:06.210 --> 00:24:10.030
Alan's work with Karen Singer
Jabbour, his wife of 55 years,

00:24:10.030 --> 00:24:13.990
represented documentary
recycling of another sort.

00:24:13.990 --> 00:24:17.390
Repeating their teamwork
from the 1960's when Karen

00:24:17.390 --> 00:24:21.030
and Alan visited the
Virginia fiddler Henry Reed

00:24:21.030 --> 00:24:23.750
and other folk musicians.

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:26.940
Their joint effort in the
2000's yielded their engaging

00:24:26.940 --> 00:24:31.180
and thoughtful book,
Decoration Day in the Mountains.

00:24:31.180 --> 00:24:34.580
I'll close with a paraphrase
of Alan's own tribute

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:39.040
to Ben Botkin, the man from whom
this lecture series is named.

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:40.890
Adjusting the words, a bit

00:24:40.890 --> 00:24:44.470
to celebrate Alan's
final phase of life.

00:24:44.470 --> 00:24:47.920
His official Washington
career was over.

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:50.620
Neither his personal
accounts, nor those of others,

00:24:50.620 --> 00:24:53.670
suggest any deep
unhappiness with the tensions

00:24:53.670 --> 00:24:56.980
of administrative life
in the federal maw.

00:24:56.980 --> 00:24:59.620
He continued to be
a public folklorist,

00:24:59.620 --> 00:25:02.100
now in a private capacity.

00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:06.210
It had been a vigorous period in
the American cultural enterprise

00:25:06.210 --> 00:25:08.430
and both Alan Jabbour
as an individual

00:25:08.430 --> 00:25:11.910
and the American Folklife Center
as a cultural institution,

00:25:11.910 --> 00:25:14.950
were at the very
epicenter of the enterprise.

00:25:14.950 --> 00:25:16.750
Thank you.

00:25:16.750 --> 00:25:36.040
[ Background noise ]

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:37.340
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson:
Thanks so much Carl.

00:25:37.340 --> 00:25:39.180
That was wonderful
and it's wonderful

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:43.040
to see all these incredible
photographs and the photographs

00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:46.500
that we saw earlier during the
reception, many of those are

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:52.890
from the field survey projects
that Alan and Carl did.

00:25:52.890 --> 00:25:55.210
Now, we are on to
our next speaker,

00:25:55.210 --> 00:25:58.830
a gentleman named
DAVID DURCHGOTT

00:25:58.830 --> 00:26:00.960
and who I have not
personally met,

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:05.960
but I know he is a contributor
to the Henry Reed fund

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:11.160
and also runs an organization
that Alan served on,

00:26:11.160 --> 00:26:14.140
on the board, International
Arts and Artists.

00:26:14.140 --> 00:26:15.440
Sort of going back to some

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:17.470
of the comments that
I made earlier.

00:26:17.470 --> 00:26:19.510
So, David, welcome.

00:26:19.510 --> 00:26:28.290
[ Background noise ]

00:26:28.290 --> 00:26:29.590
&gt;&gt; DAVID DURCHGOTT: Thank you.

00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:30.890
Thank you very much.

00:26:30.890 --> 00:26:33.740
In 1974, I was working for the
South Carolina Arts Commission

00:26:33.740 --> 00:26:38.000
and my responsibilities there
included coordinating the first

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:41.730
national endowment for the
arts funded multistate project.

00:26:41.730 --> 00:26:43.740
We were documenting
the local folk ways

00:26:43.740 --> 00:26:46.890
of the South Carolina low
country using methodology

00:26:46.890 --> 00:26:49.720
which would be simultaneously
used

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:51.940
in Mississippi and Kentucky.

00:26:51.940 --> 00:26:54.220
Alan is the director
of the nation endowment

00:26:54.220 --> 00:26:56.050
for the arts new
folk art program flew

00:26:56.050 --> 00:26:58.160
to South Carolina to meet me.

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:00.730
I picked him up at the Columbia
airport and we drove 2 hours

00:27:00.730 --> 00:27:02.980
to Charleston to
view the programs.

00:27:02.980 --> 00:27:05.190
That drive and conversation
was fascinating.

00:27:05.190 --> 00:27:07.820
It was my first exposure to Alan

00:27:07.820 --> 00:27:10.960
and like practically every other
conversation we had throughout

00:27:10.960 --> 00:27:15.400
the subsequent 42-year
friendship, it was enlightening

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:18.620
in an era prior to the
internet and Google,

00:27:18.620 --> 00:27:22.850
Alan was not only familiar with
music and the material culture

00:27:22.850 --> 00:27:26.590
of Charleston, my hometown,
but then he also knew

00:27:26.590 --> 00:27:29.470
about my family's history
and historic connection

00:27:29.470 --> 00:27:31.630
to Jacksonville, his hometown.

00:27:31.630 --> 00:27:36.230
I never left a conversation
with Alan

00:27:36.230 --> 00:27:38.840
without learning something new.

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:41.550
His interests were broad and
his knowledge was encyclopedic

00:27:41.550 --> 00:27:46.490
and thinking back to that 2-hour
drive in our original meeting,

00:27:46.490 --> 00:27:47.940
I later realized
that I could've,

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:51.510
he could've easily flown
directly to Charleston

00:27:51.510 --> 00:27:55.530
to meet me there, but I'm sure
that Alan wanted that car time

00:27:55.530 --> 00:27:58.240
to get to know who I was.

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:00.950
Within the context of this
tribute to Alan's legacy,

00:28:00.950 --> 00:28:03.670
I felt it was very important
to mention the breadth

00:28:03.670 --> 00:28:07.430
of Alan's impact went far
beyond the traditional music

00:28:07.430 --> 00:28:10.800
and folklife communities
that he loved so dearly.

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:12.620
In his work as the
first director

00:28:12.620 --> 00:28:17.780
of the folk arts program
at the NEA in 1974 to 1976,

00:28:17.780 --> 00:28:21.380
Alan helped millions bring the
arts to millions and millions

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:24.740
of people and he did it in a
way that they could understand,

00:28:24.740 --> 00:28:29.390
touching the very fiber of who
they were and where they were.

00:28:29.390 --> 00:28:32.550
Additionally, Alan personally
and directly affected the lives

00:28:32.550 --> 00:28:37.410
of 100's of people like me, who
were then working across the U.S

00:28:37.410 --> 00:28:40.830
as we could to carry
that same message.

00:28:40.830 --> 00:28:44.800
Here, in D.C., Alan
was on the board

00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:49.630
and co-chaired the humanities
D.C., which was from 1987

00:28:49.630 --> 00:28:51.600
to 1988 which is
the local affiliate

00:28:51.600 --> 00:28:54.810
of the national endowment
for the humanities.

00:28:54.810 --> 00:28:57.890
Nationally, he also helped
organize the alliance

00:28:57.890 --> 00:29:02.390
for American Quilts
from 2001 to 2007

00:29:02.390 --> 00:29:06.200
and he facilitated starting
the Quilt Alliance's national

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:08.160
documentation index.

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:10.960
He served on the
boards of the Alliance

00:29:10.960 --> 00:29:14.470
of the National Heritage
Areas, the European Center

00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:18.240
for Traditional Cultures,
and shared the fun for folk,

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:23.720
fun for folk culture, as Carl
mentioned, from 1991 to 1994.

00:29:23.720 --> 00:29:25.680
And closest to me, Alan
served on the board

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:28.490
of International Arts
and Artists for 14 years.

00:29:28.490 --> 00:29:32.920
He was our board chair for 7 and
a half years, 3 successive years

00:29:32.920 --> 00:29:38.460
at the terms May 25th of 2009
until his death last year.

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:41.450
He guided International Arts
and Artists, an organization

00:29:41.450 --> 00:29:46.260
that focuses on sharing
cultures, through the recession

00:29:46.260 --> 00:29:49.330
and with, through a lot
of organizational growth.

00:29:49.330 --> 00:29:51.120
He encouraged the
organization to reach

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:54.330
out to the broadest range of
cultures from other nations

00:29:54.330 --> 00:29:57.430
as well as to all
American ethnicities.

00:29:57.430 --> 00:30:00.510
We lived around the corner from
each other as well for 25 years.

00:30:00.510 --> 00:30:03.840
[ Background noise ]

00:30:03.840 --> 00:30:06.560
Throughout all of these
involvements, in every aspect

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:09.390
of his life, Alan was
demanding of himself,

00:30:09.390 --> 00:30:11.010
and yet showed tremendous
kindness

00:30:11.010 --> 00:30:12.820
and patience with others.

00:30:12.820 --> 00:30:17.350
He was [inaudible] and yet
in the most folksy manner.

00:30:17.350 --> 00:30:20.590
He always spoke endearingly
and proudly of his children,

00:30:20.590 --> 00:30:23.680
his love of Karen, and his
appreciation of her intellect.

00:30:23.680 --> 00:30:27.030
And her unwavering support
was evident throughout their

00:30:27.030 --> 00:30:29.240
remarkable half century
of marriage.

00:30:29.240 --> 00:30:33.630
I wanted to thank him in front
of everyone, a dear friend,

00:30:33.630 --> 00:30:36.310
who I'll miss greatly.

00:30:36.310 --> 00:30:38.110
Thank you.

00:30:38.110 --> 00:30:49.600
[ Applause ]

00:30:49.600 --> 00:30:51.560
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson:
Thank you, David.

00:30:51.560 --> 00:30:56.160
Now I want to call up to
the stage Ken Perlman,

00:30:56.160 --> 00:31:02.100
who many of you know, and
was also a partner of Alan's,

00:31:02.100 --> 00:31:03.790
and is considered to be one

00:31:03.790 --> 00:31:06.870
of the top claw hammer
banjo players in the world.

00:31:06.870 --> 00:31:09.770
Known in particular for
his skillful adaptations

00:31:09.770 --> 00:31:12.580
of Celtic tunes to the style.

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:15.560
And he draws his material
from traditional sources,

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:19.170
including the music of
Scotland, Ireland, Cape Britain,

00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:22.360
Prince Edward Island
and the American South.

00:31:22.360 --> 00:31:26.080
But his approach to the
music is highly innovative.

00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:28.950
Also, as an active
folklorist, Ken has spent

00:31:28.950 --> 00:31:32.460
over 2 decades collecting
tunes and oral histories

00:31:32.460 --> 00:31:36.420
from traditional fiddle
players on Prince Edward Island

00:31:36.420 --> 00:31:39.770
and Eastern Canada, which
has resulted in 2 books

00:31:39.770 --> 00:31:43.530
and a 2 CD anthology
of field recordings.

00:31:43.530 --> 00:31:47.330
He has toured throughout most
of the English speaking world,

00:31:47.330 --> 00:31:50.140
sometimes with Alan,
and in Western Europe,

00:31:50.140 --> 00:31:53.270
both as a soloist,
and for over 15 years,

00:31:53.270 --> 00:31:55.660
in a duo with Alan Jabbour.

00:31:55.660 --> 00:31:58.820
So, oh, you are right behind me.

00:31:58.820 --> 00:32:03.340
Okay. I didn't know if I needed
to kind of stall, but I don't.

00:32:03.340 --> 00:32:06.510
So, without further
adieu, Ken Perlman.

00:32:06.510 --> 00:32:14.480
[ Applause ]

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:16.770
&gt;&gt; Ken Perlman: Well,
thank you, so much.

00:32:16.770 --> 00:32:19.400
Before I start, I'd like
to thank Karen Jabbour

00:32:19.400 --> 00:32:25.400
for the great honor of speaking
here to remember Alan in front

00:32:25.400 --> 00:32:27.860
of so many wonderful people.

00:32:27.860 --> 00:32:38.660
Alan and I toured together,
okay, this is the, okay, got it.

00:32:38.660 --> 00:32:40.840
Sorry. Technology.

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:44.960
Alan and I toured together
for nearly 15 years.

00:32:44.960 --> 00:32:48.840
We first encountered each
other, musically, in August 2000

00:32:48.840 --> 00:32:51.080
at a music camp in the Rockies.

00:32:51.080 --> 00:32:54.480
His official accompanist
bowed out at the last minuted,

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:57.360
and given that I was the
resident old time banjo picker,

00:32:57.360 --> 00:32:59.530
he asked me to accompany
him in his concert set.

00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:02.830
From the moment he
touched bow to string,

00:33:02.830 --> 00:33:04.170
and we started playing together,

00:33:04.170 --> 00:33:07.710
there was a strong musical
affinity, an uncanny blend

00:33:07.710 --> 00:33:11.320
of fiddle tone with banjo
tone, along with a sharing

00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:13.970
of sensibilities and tastes.

00:33:13.970 --> 00:33:16.390
His approach was strong
and powerfully rhythmic,

00:33:16.390 --> 00:33:21.180
but fully lyrical and delicately
phrased, even charming.

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:24.560
As soon as I heard him interpret
a tune, even one I had heard

00:33:24.560 --> 00:33:26.610
around the scene for years,

00:33:26.610 --> 00:33:30.170
that instantly became the
definitive version for me,

00:33:30.170 --> 00:33:32.310
and one I wanted to emulate.

00:33:32.310 --> 00:33:35.100
He inspired me, not only
to learn many dozens

00:33:35.100 --> 00:33:38.770
of his tunes note for note,
but to develop a whole new way

00:33:38.770 --> 00:33:42.980
to accompany them that fit
his style like a glove.

00:33:42.980 --> 00:33:48.640
This melding of fiddle and banjo
can be heard on our first CD,

00:33:48.640 --> 00:33:56.300
Southern Summits, and jointed by
guitarist Jim Watson, I guess,

00:33:56.300 --> 00:33:59.520
who couldn't make it
at the last minute,

00:33:59.520 --> 00:34:02.120
he as going to be here
tonight,on the CD,

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:03.850
You Can't Beat the Classics,

00:34:03.850 --> 00:34:07.040
which was completed just a
few months before the onset

00:34:07.040 --> 00:34:09.460
of Alan's last illness.

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:11.730
I'd like to go back to
slide 2 for a minute,

00:34:11.730 --> 00:34:14.600
and here's a little
sample of the sound

00:34:14.600 --> 00:34:18.890
that we developed together,
a tune called Waynesboro,

00:34:18.890 --> 00:34:20.690
just a little excerpt.

00:34:20.690 --> 00:35:05.510
[ Music ]

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:08.510
[ Background noise ]

00:35:08.510 --> 00:35:14.040
[ Applause ]

00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:17.180
I can still remember
our recording it, here,

00:35:17.180 --> 00:35:21.140
in Washington, 10 years ago.

00:35:21.140 --> 00:35:23.080
After a few visits
back and forth,

00:35:23.080 --> 00:35:25.730
Alan and I started
touring, and until the state

00:35:25.730 --> 00:35:28.520
of his health intervened,
we toured or worked together

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:34.090
at music camps at least
3 or 4 times a year.

00:35:34.090 --> 00:35:38.450
Our travels took us to England,
Ireland, Scotland and Shetland,

00:35:38.450 --> 00:35:40.160
Western Europe and Canada,

00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:43.320
but mostly we toured
regionally in the United States.

00:35:43.320 --> 00:35:45.490
Depending on the season,
our travels took us

00:35:45.490 --> 00:35:49.420
to the Northeast, or
his native South Land,

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:51.770
the Pacific Coast,
or the Midwest.

00:35:51.770 --> 00:35:55.910
In what was probably our longest
tour, in the fall of 2010,

00:35:55.910 --> 00:35:58.590
we started out in Atlanta,
curved through Alabama,

00:35:58.590 --> 00:36:01.170
Tennessee and Kentucky,
on up into Michigan,

00:36:01.170 --> 00:36:03.370
headed northwest past
Chicago to Madison,

00:36:03.370 --> 00:36:06.510
and then back to
D.C. via Indiana.

00:36:06.510 --> 00:36:09.310
[ Background noise ]

00:36:09.310 --> 00:36:14.290
And here's another
picture from that era.

00:36:14.290 --> 00:36:17.980
Touring with Alan was an
eye-opening experience.

00:36:17.980 --> 00:36:21.130
He was a much loved
and respected figure,

00:36:21.130 --> 00:36:24.600
renowned not only in the folk
and acoustic music worlds,

00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:25.900
but also in the world

00:36:25.900 --> 00:36:28.350
of academic folklore,
as you've heard.

00:36:28.350 --> 00:36:30.920
Even in a world of perfect,
and near, strangers,

00:36:30.920 --> 00:36:33.960
he had only to walk in
to command attention.

00:36:33.960 --> 00:36:37.490
And most folks would emerge
from any given social occasion,

00:36:37.490 --> 00:36:40.250
deeply impressed with
his wisdom and charm.

00:36:40.250 --> 00:36:44.130
He considered himself to be as
much a storyteller as musician,

00:36:44.130 --> 00:36:48.930
and his song intros at concerts
were often quite elaborate.

00:36:48.930 --> 00:36:50.730
Nevertheless,

00:36:50.730 --> 00:36:54.040
[ Laughter ]

00:36:54.040 --> 00:36:55.590
Do you play, no.

00:36:55.590 --> 00:36:57.830
[ Laughter ]

00:36:57.830 --> 00:37:00.710
Nevertheless, audiences
hung on every word.

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:02.160
When he led jam sessions,

00:37:02.160 --> 00:37:05.630
participants would eagerly
follow wherever he led,

00:37:05.630 --> 00:37:08.320
even if they had never before
heard his selected tune

00:37:08.320 --> 00:37:10.650
or tune version.

00:37:10.650 --> 00:37:13.430
Although Alan was never
a full time musician,

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:16.500
he made incalculable
contributions

00:37:16.500 --> 00:37:18.180
to the music world.

00:37:18.180 --> 00:37:20.400
While still a graduate
student, he took his reel

00:37:20.400 --> 00:37:24.400
to reel recorder off to the
Piedmont and Southern Mountains

00:37:24.400 --> 00:37:27.640
and preserved the music of
several important roots fiddlers

00:37:27.640 --> 00:37:33.430
on tape, most notably Henry Reed
of Monroe County, West Virginia.

00:37:33.430 --> 00:37:36.060
He learned quite a number
of those tunes on fiddle,

00:37:36.060 --> 00:37:39.830
and began teaching them to
a coterie of musicians in

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:43.000
and around Chapel
Hill, North Carolina.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:48.230
Along with Bertram Levy, who
is here tonight, Bobby Thompson

00:37:48.230 --> 00:37:51.930
and Tommy Thompson, he founded
the Hollow Rock String Band,

00:37:51.930 --> 00:37:55.880
whose recordings and concerts
launched the contemporary old

00:37:55.880 --> 00:37:58.020
time music revival.

00:37:58.020 --> 00:38:00.070
The Hollow Rock band
and other products

00:38:00.070 --> 00:38:01.950
of the Chapel Hill scene,

00:38:01.950 --> 00:38:05.270
such as the Fuzzy
Mountain String Band,

00:38:05.270 --> 00:38:13.710
you can tell the era, and
the Red Clay Ramblers, same,

00:38:13.710 --> 00:38:16.440
introduced many, many
tunes to the old time scene

00:38:16.440 --> 00:38:19.000
that have become
beloved classics.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:23.880
Amongst these tunes are Over
the Waterfall, Frosty Morning,

00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:25.510
Kitchen Girl, Ebenezer,

00:38:25.510 --> 00:38:28.610
which Alan usually called
West Virginia Highway,

00:38:28.610 --> 00:38:30.510
Magpie and Green Willows.

00:38:30.510 --> 00:38:34.040
[ Background noise ]

00:38:34.040 --> 00:38:37.210
And, as you've heard, he
became the founding director

00:38:37.210 --> 00:38:39.300
of the Folklife division,
here at the Library

00:38:39.300 --> 00:38:41.250
of Congress, in the 70's.

00:38:41.250 --> 00:38:44.580
In that capacity, he promoted
music, and other folk arts,

00:38:44.580 --> 00:38:47.490
and supervised the recordings of
many additional roots musicians,

00:38:47.490 --> 00:38:49.960
most notably the Hammonds family

00:38:49.960 --> 00:38:53.200
of Pocahontas County,
West Virginia.

00:38:53.200 --> 00:38:56.170
He also had to interact with
many notable business leaders,

00:38:56.170 --> 00:38:57.730
philanthropists and politicians

00:38:57.730 --> 00:39:00.460
of the last quarter
of the 20th century.

00:39:00.460 --> 00:39:03.370
A fact that led to many
interesting conversation during

00:39:03.370 --> 00:39:06.870
our long drives between
tour destinations.

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:10.560
Thinking back on the many
stories and anecdotes

00:39:10.560 --> 00:39:13.590
that Alan shared during
our travels, I recently go

00:39:13.590 --> 00:39:16.400
to thinking that, perhaps,
one over arching theme

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:21.140
to describe his life was
the notion of the quest.

00:39:21.140 --> 00:39:24.220
What brought him to North
Carolina in the first place,

00:39:24.220 --> 00:39:27.120
was an impulse to study
someone else's quest.

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:30.340
The topic of his dissertation
was the story of Bear Wolf.

00:39:30.340 --> 00:39:34.280
Once there, he became intrigued
by the study of folklore

00:39:34.280 --> 00:39:37.120
and ballads, and
inspired by the search

00:39:37.120 --> 00:39:40.980
for child ballad melodies among
the singers of Appalachia.

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:42.520
And drawing on his background

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:45.370
as a highly trained
classical violinist,

00:39:45.370 --> 00:39:48.690
he embarked on a year's
long quest to locate

00:39:48.690 --> 00:39:53.320
and record Appalachian fiddlers
and preserve their tunes.

00:39:53.320 --> 00:39:56.790
Alan started with Piedmont
players, like John Lewis,

00:39:56.790 --> 00:40:00.160
and then headed deeper
into the mountains.

00:40:00.160 --> 00:40:03.320
He encountered a fiddler
named Oscar Wright

00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:06.540
and found himself deeply
drawn to his tunes.

00:40:06.540 --> 00:40:10.360
Wright told him that the source
of those tunes was old man,

00:40:10.360 --> 00:40:14.210
Henry Reed, who not
only was still living,

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:18.380
but could easily be tracked
down in Glen Lyn, Virginia.

00:40:18.380 --> 00:40:20.750
[ Background noise ]

00:40:20.750 --> 00:40:23.350
Alan often told the story,
you've seen that picture before,

00:40:23.350 --> 00:40:27.260
too, Alan often told the story
of how he and Karen drove

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:29.470
up to the Reed residence,
for the first time,

00:40:29.470 --> 00:40:31.980
late one afternoon,
knocked on the door,

00:40:31.980 --> 00:40:34.030
and were immediately
invited to partake

00:40:34.030 --> 00:40:37.650
of a large family dinner,
despite, as Alan puts it,

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:45.310
that Reed had no idea who we
were or why we were there, too,

00:40:45.310 --> 00:40:46.670
and be like his gestures.

00:40:46.670 --> 00:40:51.010
In any event, after dinner,
the tape recorder came out

00:40:51.010 --> 00:40:53.250
and numerous tunes
were recorded,

00:40:53.250 --> 00:40:56.210
including one called
West Virginia Gals,

00:40:56.210 --> 00:40:57.510
that Alan said moved him

00:40:57.510 --> 00:41:02.180
so deeply his musical
life was changed forever.

00:41:02.180 --> 00:41:03.940
His next quest was
learning the tunes

00:41:03.940 --> 00:41:06.510
and translating them
effectively to fiddle.

00:41:06.510 --> 00:41:08.130
Now you should know
that it's not easy

00:41:08.130 --> 00:41:12.550
for a classically trained
violinist to play fiddle music.

00:41:12.550 --> 00:41:15.510
In fact, now a days, we often
make fun of such people.

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:18.520
[ Laughter ]

00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:22.270
The bowing is completely
different, liveliness

00:41:22.270 --> 00:41:25.910
and rhythmic attack are far
more important than soaring tone

00:41:25.910 --> 00:41:28.640
and following a conductor's
directions.

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:30.720
Nevertheless, Alan
watched and listened

00:41:30.720 --> 00:41:34.610
to the old time players he met,
and figured out, not only how

00:41:34.610 --> 00:41:38.580
to play these tunes effectively,
but to play them so compellingly

00:41:38.580 --> 00:41:41.510
that they attracted a
coterie of collaborators,

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:43.930
entranced a generation
of musicians,

00:41:43.930 --> 00:41:46.510
and launched a musical revival.

00:41:46.510 --> 00:41:50.380
[ Background noise ]

00:41:50.380 --> 00:41:55.000
This said, his take on the tunes
changed as he went through life.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:57.080
Judging from the first
Hollow Rock LP's,

00:41:57.080 --> 00:42:01.840
his early playing was strong and
lively, but as the years went

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:05.520
by the quieted delicacy
of phrasing and lyricality

00:42:05.520 --> 00:42:07.490
that were truly unique
in the world

00:42:07.490 --> 00:42:10.620
of contemporary folk
music performance.

00:42:10.620 --> 00:42:13.320
And I was very fortunate to
come along right at the moment

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:14.680
that this unique approach

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:18.780
to the music was coming
fully into its own.

00:42:18.780 --> 00:42:22.280
Alan loved playing with strong
innovative banjo pickers.

00:42:22.280 --> 00:42:25.100
And working with him served
as a great inspiration

00:42:25.100 --> 00:42:28.440
to numerous influential
banjoists.

00:42:28.440 --> 00:42:31.680
Tommy Thompson, there
on the right,

00:42:31.680 --> 00:42:34.640
developed a highly percussive,
semi-melodic picking style

00:42:34.640 --> 00:42:37.650
to drive the Hollow
Rock String Band sound,

00:42:37.650 --> 00:42:41.260
and carried that style
into the Red Clay Ramblers.

00:42:41.260 --> 00:42:44.110
Many, many banjo pickers
that came up during the 70's

00:42:44.110 --> 00:42:46.470
and 80's cite Tommy's
playing as one

00:42:46.470 --> 00:42:49.530
of their main, formative
influences.

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:53.510
Bertram Levy eventually put
aside the mandolin he played

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:57.170
in his Chapel Hill days,
and took up 5 string banjo.

00:42:57.170 --> 00:43:00.960
And as he re-explored the
Hollow Rock repertoire,

00:43:00.960 --> 00:43:03.000
he developed a new
approach to claw hammer

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:05.960
that can be heard merge
with Alan's fiddling

00:43:05.960 --> 00:43:09.690
and James Reed's guitar
playing on the CD,

00:43:09.690 --> 00:43:11.590
the Henry Reed Reunion.

00:43:11.590 --> 00:43:13.440
And that's Bertram on the right.

00:43:13.440 --> 00:43:14.880
He's here tonight.

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:21.860
And then, in the 90's, banjoist
philosopher, Stephen Wade,

00:43:21.860 --> 00:43:24.550
who is also here today, and
you'll hear from him in a,

00:43:24.550 --> 00:43:28.560
very shortly, was one of Alan's
favorite musical collaborators,

00:43:28.560 --> 00:43:30.770
and in fact, a CD made from one

00:43:30.770 --> 00:43:35.860
of their live performances
has just been issued.

00:43:35.860 --> 00:43:38.060
Alan used to tell quite
a number of stories

00:43:38.060 --> 00:43:41.570
about the tunes we played,
some of which reflected

00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:44.510
on the vicissitudes of
collecting a repertory

00:43:44.510 --> 00:43:46.440
and then observing
from a distance

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:49.450
as individual tunes
became disseminated.

00:43:49.450 --> 00:43:52.500
He always regretted, for
example, that he never thought

00:43:52.500 --> 00:43:54.820
to ask fiddler John
Lewis about the spelling

00:43:54.820 --> 00:43:58.390
of the tune title,
Rose Division.

00:43:58.390 --> 00:44:02.220
He wrote down r o s e, like
the flower, but was later left

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:07.330
to wonder could it actually
have been r o w e apostrophe s,

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:11.560
or even r h o d e apostrophe s?

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:15.780
You may remember this musing.

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:21.050
Alan later found out
from, he often talked

00:44:21.050 --> 00:44:25.890
about a quirky a modal tune,
originall recorded by Reed,

00:44:25.890 --> 00:44:31.400
with no title, but dubbed
Texas by the Hollow Rock crew,

00:44:31.400 --> 00:44:32.700
when they put it on an LP,

00:44:32.700 --> 00:44:34.700
because of a story
that Reed had told.

00:44:34.700 --> 00:44:39.510
Can we hear that audio please?

00:44:39.510 --> 00:44:57.020
[ Music ]

00:44:57.020 --> 00:45:00.300
Okay. So Alan later found out,
from Reed, that the real name

00:45:00.300 --> 00:45:03.940
of the tune was Newcastle.

00:45:03.940 --> 00:45:07.470
But despite years of trying
to correct the nomenclature,

00:45:07.470 --> 00:45:10.250
people in the old time music
revival could simply not

00:45:10.250 --> 00:45:12.520
be budged.

00:45:12.520 --> 00:45:14.110
As far as they were concerned,

00:45:14.110 --> 00:45:18.300
the name of the tune was
Texas, and that was that.

00:45:18.300 --> 00:45:21.740
Another case that bemused him
involved a very sweet lyrical

00:45:21.740 --> 00:45:24.170
tune in the key of
g, again collected

00:45:24.170 --> 00:45:25.980
from Henry Reed with no title.

00:45:25.980 --> 00:45:29.510
Can we have the other tune
on that slide, please?

00:45:29.510 --> 00:45:51.620
[ Music ]

00:45:51.620 --> 00:45:55.230
Anyway, Alan included
it on a tape he sent

00:45:55.230 --> 00:45:57.950
out to the West Coast,
positioned right next

00:45:57.950 --> 00:46:01.160
to another tune called
Lady of the Lake.

00:46:01.160 --> 00:46:02.710
Somehow things got conflated,

00:46:02.710 --> 00:46:06.260
to use one of Alan's
pet expressions,

00:46:06.260 --> 00:46:09.340
and the g tune started
spreading on the West Coast

00:46:09.340 --> 00:46:12.050
under the title Lady
of the Lake.

00:46:12.050 --> 00:46:14.580
Years later, Alan was able
to trace how the tune,

00:46:14.580 --> 00:46:18.390
with its newly minted name,
moved from fiddler to fiddler,

00:46:18.390 --> 00:46:21.720
until its original provenance
was forgotten and it got

00:46:21.720 --> 00:46:24.060
into the hands of a well
known contra dance fiddler

00:46:24.060 --> 00:46:27.570
from New Hampshire,
named Rodney Miller.

00:46:27.570 --> 00:46:31.510
Miller recorded it on an LP
called New England Chestnuts.

00:46:31.510 --> 00:46:37.530
[ Laughter ]

00:46:37.530 --> 00:46:41.230
And from that time
on, virtually everyone

00:46:41.230 --> 00:46:46.260
in the folk scene has assumed
it was an old New England tune.

00:46:46.260 --> 00:46:49.470
This said, as it happens,
the title Lady of the Lake,

00:46:49.470 --> 00:46:51.130
fits the tune perfectly.

00:46:51.130 --> 00:46:54.450
And the melody is far better
suited for contra dancing

00:46:54.450 --> 00:47:00.430
than it is for southern square
dancing, so no harm done.

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:03.130
Alan often compared the
function of tune collectors

00:47:03.130 --> 00:47:06.020
to the workings of an hourglass.

00:47:06.020 --> 00:47:08.930
In an earlier era, a
given tune might be known

00:47:08.930 --> 00:47:10.970
by many musicians, then

00:47:10.970 --> 00:47:13.370
as the music culture
declines there were fewer

00:47:13.370 --> 00:47:17.040
and fewer players, and
the number of people

00:47:17.040 --> 00:47:18.880
who know the tune shrinks,

00:47:18.880 --> 00:47:22.580
sometimes to as few
as a single person.

00:47:22.580 --> 00:47:25.630
When the collector comes along,
hopefully before that last grain

00:47:25.630 --> 00:47:31.120
of sand has disappeared, he or
she teaches the tune to others.

00:47:31.120 --> 00:47:33.910
It then comes back to
life and spreads again,

00:47:33.910 --> 00:47:35.770
sometimes becoming
even better known

00:47:35.770 --> 00:47:37.570
than it was in the first place.

00:47:37.570 --> 00:47:40.880
[ Background noise ]

00:47:40.880 --> 00:47:42.800
No tune is a better
case in point, here,

00:47:42.800 --> 00:47:45.100
than Over the Waterfall.

00:47:45.100 --> 00:47:48.970
It was collected from Henry
Reed, a single known source,

00:47:48.970 --> 00:47:51.590
and spread so quickly
and pervasively

00:47:51.590 --> 00:47:55.100
that few people now a days have
any idea where it came from.

00:47:55.100 --> 00:47:57.770
It first appeared as cut
number 7 on the b side

00:47:57.770 --> 00:48:00.500
of the first Hollow Rock LP.

00:48:00.500 --> 00:48:03.790
Not long afterwards, Alan
moved to L.A. and was asked

00:48:03.790 --> 00:48:07.890
to judge a fiddle contest
at nearby Topanga Canyon.

00:48:07.890 --> 00:48:10.690
One of the contestants, not
knowing who was judging,

00:48:10.690 --> 00:48:12.810
announced that he was
going to play a tune

00:48:12.810 --> 00:48:16.010
from the Hollow Rock String
Band called Over the Waterfall.

00:48:16.010 --> 00:48:20.510
As Alan put it, that tune
beat me to California.

00:48:20.510 --> 00:48:23.780
[ Laughter ]

00:48:23.780 --> 00:48:27.740
Flash forward about 15
years, Alan and Karen were

00:48:27.740 --> 00:48:30.960
in Hungary attending a music
party, Halvic Injunction

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:34.080
with an Academic Conference,
a band from Brittany was

00:48:34.080 --> 00:48:35.750
on center stage when
the word got

00:48:35.750 --> 00:48:38.030
out that the tall
American played the fiddle,

00:48:38.030 --> 00:48:41.130
Alan was 6 6 in his
stocking feet.

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:44.700
In Alan's words, I saw the
band members talking among

00:48:44.700 --> 00:48:47.520
themselves, and I guess
they were probably saying,

00:48:47.520 --> 00:48:52.500
what song do we know that the
tall American might also know?

00:48:52.500 --> 00:48:54.940
Finally, a young woman
who served as band leader,

00:48:54.940 --> 00:48:57.420
turned to Alan and
asked brightly,

00:48:57.420 --> 00:48:59.510
can you play, Over
the Waterfall?

00:48:59.510 --> 00:49:02.350
[ Laughter ]

00:49:02.350 --> 00:49:04.750
Anyway, here's the version
of Over the Waterfall

00:49:04.750 --> 00:49:08.830
from the Hollow Rock recording
that, on that fateful,

00:49:08.830 --> 00:49:11.010
when that fateful cut was made.

00:49:11.010 --> 00:49:13.510
[ Background noise ]

00:49:13.510 --> 00:49:29.470
[ Music ]

00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:32.390
Maybe we'll get a chance to
play that in the jam session.

00:49:32.390 --> 00:49:37.660
Anyway, I'd like to conclude by
playing Billy in the Lowland,

00:49:37.660 --> 00:49:41.470
and this is a tune that Alan
and I felt was the best vehicle

00:49:41.470 --> 00:49:44.590
for capturing the essence
of our sound, and the tune

00:49:44.590 --> 00:49:47.160
that we almost always
used to open our concerts.

00:49:47.160 --> 00:49:49.800
Not surprisingly, it was
collected from Henry Reed,

00:49:49.800 --> 00:49:52.820
who said it was originally from
east Virginia, which is the way

00:49:52.820 --> 00:49:54.120
that West Virginian's refer

00:49:54.120 --> 00:49:56.510
to what is now called
the state of Virginia.

00:49:56.510 --> 00:49:59.510
[ Laughter ]

00:49:59.510 --> 00:50:13.280
[ Background noise ]

00:50:13.280 --> 00:50:15.580
I think a tuning would
be appropriate here.

00:50:15.580 --> 00:50:17.510
It is a banjo, after all.

00:50:17.510 --> 00:52:04.510
[ Music ]

00:52:04.510 --> 00:52:20.100
[ Applause ]

00:52:20.100 --> 00:52:21.400
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson:
Thank you, so much.

00:52:21.400 --> 00:52:22.850
That was really wonderful.

00:52:22.850 --> 00:52:29.040
I also want to say, that there
are some CD's in the back

00:52:29.040 --> 00:52:33.820
by Ken, both, and by
Stephen Wade who we will here

00:52:33.820 --> 00:52:36.120
from in just a second.

00:52:36.120 --> 00:52:40.410
They are recordings that are
with Alan, so if you would

00:52:40.410 --> 00:52:46.370
like to hear more, please
go back and get a copy.

00:52:46.370 --> 00:52:47.670
I'm also looking forward

00:52:47.670 --> 00:52:50.040
to hearing more music,
very shortly.

00:52:50.040 --> 00:52:53.340
It's wonderful to hear
the full dimensions

00:52:53.340 --> 00:52:55.650
of Alan being talked about here.

00:52:55.650 --> 00:53:00.170
For some of us, folklore,
as we get sort of mired

00:53:00.170 --> 00:53:04.950
in the academic and the
words, it's sure nice

00:53:04.950 --> 00:53:06.860
to hear words with music.

00:53:06.860 --> 00:53:12.700
Our next speaker is Stephen
Wade, and many of you know him.

00:53:12.700 --> 00:53:15.850
He has spent nearly his
entire life in the study

00:53:15.850 --> 00:53:19.240
of American folklife, and
he's probably best known

00:53:19.240 --> 00:53:22.230
for banjo dancing, a
theatrical performance

00:53:22.230 --> 00:53:25.140
that combines storytelling,
traditional music,

00:53:25.140 --> 00:53:27.590
and percussive dance,
which was one

00:53:27.590 --> 00:53:31.400
of the longest running off
Broadway shows in the country.

00:53:31.400 --> 00:53:35.780
Here, at the Library, we are
particularly appreciative

00:53:35.780 --> 00:53:40.220
of his book, The Beautiful Music
All Around Us, Field Recordings

00:53:40.220 --> 00:53:42.510
and the American Experience,

00:53:42.510 --> 00:53:45.540
which showcases nearly
two decades of research,

00:53:45.540 --> 00:53:49.300
during which Wade tracked
down the communities, families

00:53:49.300 --> 00:53:53.580
and performers connected with
the iconic AFC field recordings,

00:53:53.580 --> 00:53:58.660
and do, indeed, demonstrate
how important research is.

00:53:58.660 --> 00:54:03.080
The book received the 2013
ASCAP Deem's Taylor Award,

00:54:03.080 --> 00:54:06.500
and the Association of
Recorded Sound Collections Award

00:54:06.500 --> 00:54:08.710
for Best History.

00:54:08.710 --> 00:54:12.590
Wade has released a number
of award winning CD's,

00:54:12.590 --> 00:54:16.750
of which the latest is
Americana Concert, Alan Jabbour

00:54:16.750 --> 00:54:19.200
and Stephen Wade at the
Library of Congress.

00:54:19.200 --> 00:54:22.510
So please, give a warm
welcome to Stephen Wade.

00:54:22.510 --> 00:54:34.210
[ Applause ]

00:54:34.210 --> 00:54:36.830
&gt;&gt; Stephen Wade: Alan and
I would always open all

00:54:36.830 --> 00:54:39.240
of our shows with
this tune here.

00:54:39.240 --> 00:54:45.240
We started playing together,
I met him in 19 mid 70's,

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:49.510
and we started playing
here in DC around 82.

00:54:49.510 --> 00:54:52.040
[ Music ]

00:54:52.040 --> 00:54:53.420
You're ready there?

00:54:53.420 --> 00:54:54.720
All right.

00:54:54.720 --> 00:54:57.510
That's Zan McLeod, and he was
a good friend of Alan's, too.

00:54:57.510 --> 00:55:02.130
[ Applause ]

00:55:02.130 --> 00:55:06.510
When my wife and I got married,
Zan and Alan played that.

00:55:06.510 --> 00:57:01.510
[ Music ]

00:57:01.510 --> 00:57:11.500
[ Applause ]

00:57:11.500 --> 00:57:13.600
Thank you, very much.

00:57:13.600 --> 00:57:16.320
Well, as I said, Alan and
I opened our every concert

00:57:16.320 --> 00:57:19.370
with that tune, that
he called Stony Point.

00:57:19.370 --> 00:57:21.460
But it goes by more
names than that.

00:57:21.460 --> 00:57:26.920
These include, Old Vad,
Wild Horse, Celtin's Reel,

00:57:26.920 --> 00:57:32.300
Pig Town Fling, Unfortunate
Dog, Buck Creek Girl,

00:57:32.300 --> 00:57:35.250
Richmond Ruckus, and when
Earl Scruggs recorded it

00:57:35.250 --> 00:57:39.560
with Paul Warren, they
called it Fiddling Banjo.

00:57:39.560 --> 00:57:41.640
Back when we performed it,

00:57:41.640 --> 00:57:45.700
Alan noted that there'd always
be some accommodating soul,

00:57:45.700 --> 00:57:49.580
he said, who would call it
the Wild Horse at Stony Point.

00:57:49.580 --> 00:57:52.640
I thought of a way of
approaching this tune

00:57:52.640 --> 00:57:55.720
without Alan here to lead it
might reside in that banjo here,

00:57:55.720 --> 00:57:57.530
made during the Civil War.

00:57:57.530 --> 00:58:01.300
The history that dwells in this
instrument, and the past lives

00:58:01.300 --> 00:58:05.480
who once held it, calls to mind
the remark that Alan often made

00:58:05.480 --> 00:58:09.370
about Quince Dillion, a fiddler
in fifer from the Mexican War,

00:58:09.370 --> 00:58:12.890
who, as an old man,
taught young Henry Reed,

00:58:12.890 --> 00:58:17.300
who then decades later, guided
the youthful Alan Jabbour.

00:58:17.300 --> 00:58:21.680
Only one person Alan
marveled stood between himself

00:58:21.680 --> 00:58:25.190
and that misty figure
of Jacksonian America,

00:58:25.190 --> 00:58:28.620
that tenacious thread
still intact extends

00:58:28.620 --> 00:58:30.510
to those here tonight,

00:58:30.510 --> 00:58:33.790
who in turn learn
their music from Alan.

00:58:33.790 --> 00:58:38.720
And thus, ancestries
become continuities.

00:58:38.720 --> 00:58:43.590
The epigraph of this new album,
a concert that Alan and I played

00:58:43.590 --> 00:58:46.750
at the Coolidge Auditorium
20 years ago,

00:58:46.750 --> 00:58:49.280
comes from something Alan wrote.

00:58:49.280 --> 00:58:52.860
He said, how complicated
and powerful,

00:58:52.860 --> 00:58:57.760
beyond our own imaginings, are
the radiations of what we do.

00:58:57.760 --> 00:59:00.470
Alan's thought applies not only

00:59:00.470 --> 00:59:03.680
to the influences his
repertory had upon others,

00:59:03.680 --> 00:59:05.920
but within the music itself.

00:59:05.920 --> 00:59:09.260
Alan exemplified an
approach that Indian fiddler,

00:59:09.260 --> 00:59:12.510
John W. Summers, a
contemporary of Henry Reed's,

00:59:12.510 --> 00:59:16.110
called the originality
of the tune.

00:59:16.110 --> 00:59:21.650
That is, that each piece
possesses a detailed identity.

00:59:21.650 --> 00:59:24.880
Dick Summers saw it as
the fiddler's obligation

00:59:24.880 --> 00:59:28.250
to learn however many
parts a tune might have,

00:59:28.250 --> 00:59:33.180
and to take no shortcuts in
that, in their execution.

00:59:33.180 --> 00:59:37.220
Similarly, Buddy Thomas, a
Kentucky fiddler committed

00:59:37.220 --> 00:59:41.910
to the older styles, felt
the need to bow the tune out.

00:59:41.910 --> 00:59:45.100
The influential radio
fiddler, Georgia Slim Rutland,

00:59:45.100 --> 00:59:48.390
likewise spoke of
his mother's council,

00:59:48.390 --> 00:59:49.850
when he first started playing.

00:59:49.850 --> 00:59:52.980
She said, don't ever
detract from a tune.

00:59:52.980 --> 00:59:55.740
Add to it all you want,
but don't take away.

00:59:55.740 --> 01:00:00.810
These musicians shared, in
common, a view of fiddle tunes

01:00:00.810 --> 01:00:04.280
as complex, self-contained
works.

01:00:04.280 --> 01:00:07.510
And that's how Alan
crafted his pieces.

01:00:07.510 --> 01:00:18.510
[ Background noise ]

01:00:18.510 --> 01:03:38.510
[ Music ]

01:03:38.510 --> 01:03:52.510
[ Applause ]

01:03:52.510 --> 01:03:56.970
[ Background noise ]

01:03:56.970 --> 01:04:01.660
Tonight's invitation also
asks us to also consider Alan

01:04:01.660 --> 01:04:04.610
in relation to his
legacy in folk life.

01:04:04.610 --> 01:04:07.320
When Alan began his
graduate studies at Duke,

01:04:07.320 --> 01:04:11.260
his classroom professor
sometimes played selections

01:04:11.260 --> 01:04:13.150
from the folk music
albums issued

01:04:13.150 --> 01:04:15.790
by the Library of Congress.

01:04:15.790 --> 01:04:19.590
These performances, many
recorded in domestic settings,

01:04:19.590 --> 01:04:22.830
did not scrub away the
sounds of those places.

01:04:22.830 --> 01:04:25.980
In the background,
sometimes, a dog barks,

01:04:25.980 --> 01:04:31.340
a kitchen clock ticks, roosters
crow, a truck drives by,

01:04:31.340 --> 01:04:33.840
these records alerted
Alan to the kind

01:04:33.840 --> 01:04:37.880
of first person collecting
he soon undertook himself,

01:04:37.880 --> 01:04:42.380
nor in the ensuring years,
as head of the folk archive

01:04:42.380 --> 01:04:44.450
and later as director of the
American Folklife Center,

01:04:44.450 --> 01:04:47.700
did he divorce cultural
expression

01:04:47.700 --> 01:04:50.500
from lived experience.

01:04:50.500 --> 01:04:53.850
Art is not a thing
apart, he once told me,

01:04:53.850 --> 01:04:56.870
it can't be set aside from life.

01:04:56.870 --> 01:05:00.400
One song emblematic of
that fusion, and included

01:05:00.400 --> 01:05:04.660
on those albums that Alan heard,
comes from Vera Hall, a singer

01:05:04.660 --> 01:05:07.420
and domestic worker from
Livingston, Alabama.

01:05:07.420 --> 01:05:10.510
In October, 1940, she
recorded for the Library,

01:05:10.510 --> 01:05:13.830
Another Man Done Gone,
a blues she learned

01:05:13.830 --> 01:05:17.330
from her husband recently
returned from prison.

01:05:17.330 --> 01:05:20.180
Well, the well known
number most often appears

01:05:20.180 --> 01:05:21.720
as a lover's plaint.

01:05:21.720 --> 01:05:25.070
In her rendition, she
largely sang spirituals,

01:05:25.070 --> 01:05:28.420
it seemingly becomes
a civil rights anthem.

01:05:28.420 --> 01:05:31.110
In what could serve
as a mission statement

01:05:31.110 --> 01:05:35.590
for the American Folklife
Center, Vera Hall later said,

01:05:35.590 --> 01:05:38.500
any song that we
sing have reference

01:05:38.500 --> 01:05:40.510
to the life that we live.

01:05:40.510 --> 01:05:59.510
[ Background noise ]

01:05:59.510 --> 01:09:38.510
[ Music ]

01:09:38.510 --> 01:09:52.510
[ Applause ]

01:09:52.510 --> 01:09:55.230
[ Background noise ]

01:09:55.230 --> 01:09:57.760
Well, he closed with a medley.

01:09:57.760 --> 01:10:01.310
The first recalls a tune
that Alan played as Patty

01:10:01.310 --> 01:10:05.530
on the turnpike, though it,
too, goes by other names.

01:10:05.530 --> 01:10:08.170
We follow with Kitchen
Girl, that Alan learned

01:10:08.170 --> 01:10:11.780
from Henry Reed and then
transmitted to the world,

01:10:11.780 --> 01:10:16.100
and we end with Sheep Shell Corn
by the Rattling of His Horn,

01:10:16.100 --> 01:10:20.350
a piece recorded in 1941
for the Library of Congress

01:10:20.350 --> 01:10:22.500
by Fiddler Emmett Lundy.

01:10:22.500 --> 01:10:26.880
Lundy, born in southwest
Virginia in 1864,

01:10:26.880 --> 01:10:30.820
learned from a much older
fiddler named Green Leonard.

01:10:30.820 --> 01:10:34.370
He said of Green Leonard, quote,
he didn't teach them tunes

01:10:34.370 --> 01:10:37.180
to me, but I catched
them from him.

01:10:37.180 --> 01:10:42.000
And in his last days, he told
me that I was the only one

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:44.310
that tracked him
down, and he wanted

01:10:44.310 --> 01:10:47.350
to learn me some old
pieces before he died,

01:10:47.350 --> 01:10:49.730
he didn't want them
to be buried,

01:10:49.730 --> 01:10:54.000
and live after he was done.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:57.790
Sheep Shell Corn lives
on through Emmett Lundy.

01:10:57.790 --> 01:11:02.930
He played it majestically, a
description that applies as much

01:11:02.930 --> 01:11:10.030
to Alan Jabbour, this tall swan
of a man, musician, folklorist,

01:11:10.030 --> 01:11:17.640
administrator, author and
inspiration to so many.

01:11:17.640 --> 01:11:20.510
I hear,

01:11:20.510 --> 01:11:23.420
[ Applause ]

01:11:23.420 --> 01:11:29.970
I hear now, since he left us,
Alan's courtly words resound,

01:11:29.970 --> 01:11:34.560
how complicated and powerful,
beyond our own imaginings,

01:11:34.560 --> 01:11:37.510
are the radiations
of what we do.

01:11:37.510 --> 01:11:52.510
[ Background noise ]

01:11:52.510 --> 01:15:45.510
[ Music ]

01:15:45.510 --> 01:15:48.100
[ Applause ]

01:15:48.100 --> 01:15:50.110
That's Zan McLeod.

01:15:50.110 --> 01:15:51.910
Thank you.

01:15:51.910 --> 01:16:03.140
[ Applause ]

01:16:03.140 --> 01:16:04.440
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson:
Thank you, Stephen.

01:16:04.440 --> 01:16:06.070
Thank you, Zan.

01:16:06.070 --> 01:16:08.400
[ Background noise ]

01:16:08.400 --> 01:16:12.450
And we are coming down
to our last speaker.

01:16:12.450 --> 01:16:16.480
I think the Jabbour family
should always have the last

01:16:16.480 --> 01:16:21.190
word, before we start hearing
some music, and playing music.

01:16:21.190 --> 01:16:23.280
So please do not go away.

01:16:23.280 --> 01:16:28.190
But to come down to the, you
know, the practical universe,

01:16:28.190 --> 01:16:33.740
if you do need to leave,
there are staff at the back

01:16:33.740 --> 01:16:36.120
and will guide you
to the elevators,

01:16:36.120 --> 01:16:38.470
and make sure you
get on your way.

01:16:38.470 --> 01:16:41.660
And for those of you who stick
around, and play an instrument,

01:16:41.660 --> 01:16:44.150
and have an instrument with
you, please don't forget

01:16:44.150 --> 01:16:45.710
about those property passes.

01:16:45.710 --> 01:16:48.880
We want to make sure
you get out.

01:16:48.880 --> 01:16:53.860
So, and then finally, thank you,
Stephen, again, thank you Zan,

01:16:53.860 --> 01:16:58.490
thank you, Ken, and thank you
Carl, and thank you, Alan.

01:16:58.490 --> 01:17:03.540
Our last speaker is Karen
Jabbour, she's Alan's wife,

01:17:03.540 --> 01:17:09.050
love and lifelong research
partner throughout his career.

01:17:09.050 --> 01:17:12.010
Their work together
includes rich documentation

01:17:12.010 --> 01:17:14.820
of the tradition of Decoration
Day, which was published

01:17:14.820 --> 01:17:17.750
in the book, Decoration
Day in the Mountains,

01:17:17.750 --> 01:17:20.820
and I think she need
no other introduction.

01:17:20.820 --> 01:17:22.620
Karen.

01:17:22.620 --> 01:17:40.310
[ Applause ]

01:17:40.310 --> 01:17:43.870
&gt;&gt; Karen Jabbour: Good evening,
family and many friends.

01:17:43.870 --> 01:17:47.080
Welcoming all of you
here has reminded me

01:17:47.080 --> 01:17:48.810
of a generous reflection

01:17:48.810 --> 01:17:52.220
that Alan's first
administrative assistant,

01:17:52.220 --> 01:17:56.060
here at the American
Folklife Center, made.

01:17:56.060 --> 01:18:01.420
Eleanor Sreb said that her late
husband didn't leave her a lot

01:18:01.420 --> 01:18:08.050
of money, but he left
her very rich in friends.

01:18:08.050 --> 01:18:12.440
And I certainly feel
rich in friends tonight.

01:18:12.440 --> 01:18:18.210
My thanks to the Folklife Center
staff for their dedication

01:18:18.210 --> 01:18:22.810
in bringing about this
tribute to Alan's legacy.

01:18:22.810 --> 01:18:26.210
And my heartfelt appreciation
to Carl Fleishhauer,

01:18:26.210 --> 01:18:31.230
to David Furchgott, to Ken
Perlman, and Stephen Wade,

01:18:31.230 --> 01:18:35.850
and Zan McLeod for their
devotion to portraying for all

01:18:35.850 --> 01:18:39.950
of us, in words,
photographs and music,

01:18:39.950 --> 01:18:44.310
and their long creative
interaction with Alan.

01:18:44.310 --> 01:18:49.500
Finally, thanks to you musicians
who will continue the legacy

01:18:49.500 --> 01:18:54.110
in your tribute in
the jam later tonight.

01:18:54.110 --> 01:18:59.580
As many of you know, when
Alan retired in 1999,

01:18:59.580 --> 01:19:02.020
he took on a project
offered to him

01:19:02.020 --> 01:19:05.500
by the National Parks
Service to create a study

01:19:05.500 --> 01:19:06.980
of the cultural tradition

01:19:06.980 --> 01:19:10.300
of holding cemetery
decoration events

01:19:10.300 --> 01:19:15.160
for the environmental impact
statement for a major road

01:19:15.160 --> 01:19:18.190
in Great Smokey Mountains
National Park

01:19:18.190 --> 01:19:22.530
to the graveyards left
behind by the people

01:19:22.530 --> 01:19:27.240
who were moved off the land.

01:19:27.240 --> 01:19:32.840
Without Carl to rely on for
documentation, Alan drafted me

01:19:32.840 --> 01:19:37.270
as his field collaborator
and photographer.

01:19:37.270 --> 01:19:42.220
I can take a picture, this
is my photograph of Alan,

01:19:42.220 --> 01:19:47.520
which has been very hard for
me to look in the eye tonight,

01:19:47.520 --> 01:19:50.350
because I know he's
looking right at me.

01:19:50.350 --> 01:19:55.230
So after 2 years of attending
these cemetery events,

01:19:55.230 --> 01:19:59.330
we submitted the study
for the EIS volume.

01:19:59.330 --> 01:20:03.960
With so much enthusiasm and
documentation left over,

01:20:03.960 --> 01:20:08.920
that we went on to publish a
book in 2010 with University

01:20:08.920 --> 01:20:12.900
of North Carolina Press, called
Decoration Day in the Mountains,

01:20:12.900 --> 01:20:16.110
which has been mentioned
tonight.

01:20:16.110 --> 01:20:20.790
This only wet Alan's appetite
to continue surveying cemeteries

01:20:20.790 --> 01:20:24.780
with me, throughout
the entire rural south.

01:20:24.780 --> 01:20:28.860
And he completed, before
his death, a second book,

01:20:28.860 --> 01:20:33.480
now awaiting my editing, at the
University Press of Mississippi.

01:20:33.480 --> 01:20:38.400
In the course of studying
cemetery traditions,

01:20:38.400 --> 01:20:43.150
we researched illusions in the
literature, in literature art

01:20:43.150 --> 01:20:47.280
and song to cemetery events.

01:20:47.280 --> 01:20:51.780
Alan had a special place
in his heart for slow airs,

01:20:51.780 --> 01:20:56.360
called hens, played
by southern fiddlers.

01:20:56.360 --> 01:21:01.310
When we were doing research
at Boreal College Library,

01:21:01.310 --> 01:21:04.730
he heard a solo version
of the 19th century hymn,

01:21:04.730 --> 01:21:09.840
the Old Church Yard,
played by Sanford Kelly.

01:21:09.840 --> 01:21:14.390
And he recalled an illusion
in John C. Campbell's book,

01:21:14.390 --> 01:21:17.590
the Appalachian Highlander
in His Home,

01:21:17.590 --> 01:21:22.510
to a congregation
singing this hymn

01:21:22.510 --> 01:21:26.120
in a processional
to the cemetery.

01:21:26.120 --> 01:21:31.950
Alan noted in Kelly's playing,
the slow, monophonic style

01:21:31.950 --> 01:21:39.870
and irregular pulse of the old
unaccompanied singing style.

01:21:39.870 --> 01:21:44.410
I'd like to conclude by playing,
for you, Alan's fiddling

01:21:44.410 --> 01:21:50.580
of the Old Church Yard, the
final track on his last album,

01:21:50.580 --> 01:21:52.890
You Can't Beat the Classics.

01:21:52.890 --> 01:21:59.520
The words to the first verse
are, Oh come, come with me

01:21:59.520 --> 01:22:03.360
to the old grave yard,
I well know the path

01:22:03.360 --> 01:22:08.650
through the soft green sward,
friends slumber we would want

01:22:08.650 --> 01:22:14.510
to regard, we'll trace out their
names in the old grave yard.

01:22:14.510 --> 01:24:52.510
[ Music ]

01:24:52.510 --> 01:25:06.540
[ Applause ]

01:25:06.540 --> 01:25:10.510
Thank you, folks, and Ken
will now organize the jam.

01:25:10.510 --> 01:25:18.100
[ Applause ]

01:25:18.100 --> 01:25:21.010
&gt;&gt; Okay. So here's
a moment a lot

01:25:21.010 --> 01:25:23.700
of you have been
looking forward to.

01:25:23.700 --> 01:25:26.910
What we're going to do is
everybody whose brought

01:25:26.910 --> 01:25:29.500
instruments, this is
your time to go get them.

01:25:29.500 --> 01:25:32.960
And we'd like to clear, make
a clearing, kind of here,

01:25:32.960 --> 01:25:38.230
a big circle space
that people can come

01:25:38.230 --> 01:25:42.720
and join once you've got your
instruments, and others can sit

01:25:42.720 --> 01:25:44.810
around and listen
or participate.

01:25:44.810 --> 01:25:47.950
But we'd like to clear
some chairs right here,

01:25:47.950 --> 01:25:51.210
and make an opening that
people can sit around.

01:25:51.210 --> 01:25:56.660
&gt;&gt; The first tune we're going to
play is often called Ebenezer.

01:25:56.660 --> 01:26:00.390
And this is collected
from Henry Reed and was

01:26:00.390 --> 01:26:05.370
on the first Hollow Rock
album, and Alan said

01:26:05.370 --> 01:26:10.430
that Henry Reed often called
it West Virginia Highway.

01:26:10.430 --> 01:26:15.000
And if anyone else has
any memories to share.

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:17.980
So we're going to
start this tune.

01:26:17.980 --> 01:26:19.420
Do you want to kick it off?

01:26:19.420 --> 01:26:24.510
This is Bertram Levy, by the
way, an original Hollow Rocker.

01:26:24.510 --> 01:26:28.550
[ Applause ]

01:26:28.550 --> 01:26:32.010
&gt;&gt; I should say, right off the
bat, that this is Alan's fiddle.

01:26:32.010 --> 01:26:34.510
[ Cheering ]

01:26:34.510 --> 01:26:43.510
[ Background noise ]

01:26:43.510 --> 01:29:43.510
[ Music ]

01:29:43.510 --> 01:29:48.450
[ Applause ]

01:29:48.450 --> 01:29:50.250
&gt;&gt; Bertram, do you
want to pick a tune?

01:29:50.250 --> 01:29:52.480
[ Background noise ]

01:29:52.480 --> 01:29:54.290
Yeah, for a little while.

01:29:54.290 --> 01:30:02.460
Yeah. So, you know Alan and
I, we were like brothers,

01:30:02.460 --> 01:30:06.510
we grew up together
with this music.

01:30:06.510 --> 01:30:12.280
I mean, Alan was kind of, I
mean he was the inspiration,

01:30:12.280 --> 01:30:16.780
but we were the, 3 or 4 of us
were the people that really kind

01:30:16.780 --> 01:30:19.290
of put it all together
and made it come alive

01:30:19.290 --> 01:30:22.010
and we shared the tunes
and we shared the whiskey

01:30:22.010 --> 01:30:25.410
and the camels and we shared
being bad boys and we.

01:30:25.410 --> 01:30:31.240
It was a great experience
and I'll just relate one,

01:30:31.240 --> 01:30:34.590
one memory which is
once we visited Henry.

01:30:34.590 --> 01:30:38.240
I was his sidekick and I would
go with him to visit some

01:30:38.240 --> 01:30:40.960
of these folks and we
visited Henry and took him

01:30:40.960 --> 01:30:48.820
down to Narrows and we sat under
a tent and Alan was sitting here

01:30:48.820 --> 01:30:54.150
and Bobby Thompson was sitting
here and I was sitting there

01:30:54.150 --> 01:30:55.520
and Tommy Thompson
was sitting there

01:30:55.520 --> 01:30:58.630
and Henry was sitting there and
he hadn't been out of his house

01:30:58.630 --> 01:31:01.860
in many years and
people would all come up

01:31:01.860 --> 01:31:05.200
and offer him something to
drink and they'd all go,

01:31:05.200 --> 01:31:07.170
they'd point it out
and they say Henry,

01:31:07.170 --> 01:31:09.050
that's you when you were young.

01:31:09.050 --> 01:31:14.000
So, that was, we knew then
that Alan had the right stuff.

01:31:14.000 --> 01:31:19.010
So, this is a beautiful tune
which is John Brown's March.

01:31:19.010 --> 01:31:38.940
Remember the 4, begins with
a 4 chord on the second part.

01:32:23.510 --> 01:32:30.510
[ Background noise ]

01:32:30.510 --> 01:35:13.680
[ Music ]

01:35:13.680 --> 01:35:19.620
&gt;&gt; Hey. That wasn't a
Henry V. tune, was it?

01:35:19.620 --> 01:35:23.510
It was? Marcie do you have a
tune that you'd like us to play?

01:35:23.510 --> 01:35:30.040
[ Background noise ]

01:35:30.040 --> 01:35:31.380
&gt;&gt; Well, okay.

01:35:31.380 --> 01:35:37.290
Okay, we're going to do
Sheers and Stockings.

01:35:37.290 --> 01:35:42.770
Do you have any stories
about that other

01:35:42.770 --> 01:35:46.520
than it's a Henry V. tune?

01:35:46.520 --> 01:35:48.620
&gt;&gt; I think we actually
named this tune.

01:35:48.620 --> 01:35:52.700
I don't think Henry had
a name for it, did he?

01:35:52.700 --> 01:35:54.000
Yeah, the title.

01:35:54.000 --> 01:35:57.980
There were many tunes that
Henry didn't remember the title

01:35:57.980 --> 01:36:02.860
or sometimes we'd play
them with the one title

01:36:02.860 --> 01:36:04.400
and then he'd write back to Alan

01:36:04.400 --> 01:36:07.850
and he'd say I think that's a
different title, but now that I,

01:36:07.850 --> 01:36:15.590
you know, when I, last
time I talked to Alan,

01:36:15.590 --> 01:36:20.400
last time I talked to Alan, he,
we were musing about the facts

01:36:20.400 --> 01:36:23.550
that during our working we
always wondered while the old

01:36:23.550 --> 01:36:26.690
guys never played the fiddle
when they were working.

01:36:26.690 --> 01:36:28.880
When they were young men
and only took it up again

01:36:28.880 --> 01:36:32.750
when they were older and
then Alan and I were musing

01:36:32.750 --> 01:36:36.960
about 6 months before he
passed away and we realized

01:36:36.960 --> 01:36:40.580
that we also picked
up the fiddle again

01:36:40.580 --> 01:36:46.470
after we stopped working and I
said Alan, we were those guys

01:36:46.470 --> 01:36:48.310
and we didn't know it.

01:36:48.310 --> 01:36:51.020
We thought we were maybe
documentarians or something,

01:36:51.020 --> 01:36:53.850
but we were just
fiddlers just like them

01:36:53.850 --> 01:36:55.170
and you probably are the same.

01:36:55.170 --> 01:36:57.510
So, this is Sheers
and Stockings.

01:36:57.510 --> 01:42:41.360
[ Music ]

01:42:41.360 --> 01:42:45.970
&gt;&gt; Okay. Do you have a
tune you'd like to suggest?

01:42:45.970 --> 01:42:49.020
&gt;&gt; Green Willis.

01:42:49.020 --> 01:42:51.200
&gt;&gt; Green Willis,
you want to do to d?

01:42:51.200 --> 01:42:54.670
Banjo players mind going to d?

01:42:54.670 --> 01:42:59.830
Okay, but that's all right
we're in the territory.

01:42:59.830 --> 01:43:01.270
Okay, so we're going to D

01:43:01.270 --> 01:43:05.510
and we're going to
play Green Willis.

01:43:05.510 --> 01:44:06.040
[ Background noise ]

01:44:06.040 --> 01:44:08.370
&gt;&gt; Okay, we're going
to play Green Willis

01:44:08.370 --> 01:44:14.190
and this originated actually as
a jig called the New Rig Ship,

01:44:14.190 --> 01:44:20.840
a Scottish tune and during
the late 19th century became a

01:44:20.840 --> 01:44:25.120
fifing tune played as
a march or quickstep

01:44:25.120 --> 01:44:30.080
in the south called Chapel Hill
Serenade and then it got sped

01:44:30.080 --> 01:44:33.580
up into a reel and
that's how we play it now.

01:44:33.580 --> 01:44:38.870
So, let's start, you'd be
interested in knowing that.

01:44:38.870 --> 01:44:43.380
&gt;&gt; Once Alan and I were
sitting around with Libba Cotton

01:44:43.380 --> 01:44:46.930
and she said, I know that
tune, we used to call

01:44:46.930 --> 01:44:49.230
that Chapel Hill Serenade
when I lived there.

01:44:49.230 --> 01:44:51.290
We used to hear the
fife and drum march

01:44:51.290 --> 01:44:54.510
down the street playing
that tune and.

01:44:54.510 --> 01:45:01.510
[ Background noise ]

01:45:01.510 --> 01:48:48.070
[ Music ]

01:48:48.070 --> 01:48:50.560
&gt;&gt; Okay. So, going
around in this end

01:48:50.560 --> 01:48:52.670
of the circle, a detune.

01:48:52.670 --> 01:48:56.610
How could we not?

01:48:56.610 --> 01:49:01.140
So, you've already heard
the story of this one.

01:49:01.140 --> 01:49:02.440
Do you know anything more

01:49:02.440 --> 01:49:07.920
about Over the Waterfalls
and what I say?

01:49:07.920 --> 01:49:12.350
David, you had a story
you wanted to tell about?

01:49:12.350 --> 01:49:13.650
&gt;&gt; DAVID DURCHGOTT: All,

01:49:13.650 --> 01:49:14.950
all I know about Over
the Waterfall is it comes

01:49:14.950 --> 01:49:18.690
from an old English ballad
in which she tried, the,

01:49:18.690 --> 01:49:22.750
she wanted to get
rid of her husband

01:49:22.750 --> 01:49:26.910
and so she gave him some wine
and blinded him and sat him

01:49:26.910 --> 01:49:32.870
by the cliff and then he said,
she said just stand there

01:49:32.870 --> 01:49:36.800
and she got back and she
ran to push him over,

01:49:36.800 --> 01:49:39.760
but he was a crafty old guy and
he just stepped out of the way

01:49:39.760 --> 01:49:42.510
and she went over the waterfall.

01:49:42.510 --> 01:49:52.510
[ Background noise ]

01:49:52.510 --> 01:53:33.220
[ Music ]

01:53:33.220 --> 01:53:41.560
&gt;&gt; Okay, kind of in this end of
the circle, anyone have a tune?

01:53:41.560 --> 01:53:45.200
Rocking the Babies
to Sleep, cool.

01:53:45.200 --> 01:53:48.180
Can you play that?

01:53:48.180 --> 01:53:55.290
All right, you want to lead it?

01:53:55.290 --> 01:53:56.590
Okay.

01:53:56.590 --> 01:53:57.900
&gt;&gt; You know this [inaudible]
over here, he's the one

01:53:57.900 --> 01:53:59.300
who taught it to
Alan didn't you rock,

01:53:59.300 --> 01:54:02.510
or you at least Rocking
the Babies to Sleep.

